        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>IMAGING REQUIREMENT:  The maximum angular size scale that we would like to image is about 2.5 arcsec, while we request angular resolution of 0.09 arcsec at 691.38 GHz. According to the OT and Table A.2. in the “Proposer’s Guide”, such an imaging is feasible with the 12-m array only. If each CO outflow lobe has an extent of ~2.5 arcsec, namely, in the case that the whole structure ( = total extent of the bipolar outflow) has  ~5 arcsec, it does not fit within ~1/3 of the primary beam (theta_HPBW = 8.9 arcsec). We therefore propose two-field imaging so that each field can cover each lobe. We stress that we do *NOT* need to image the possible ~5 arcsec structure because the bipolar blue- and red-lobes do not appear in the same LSR-velocity range. On the other hand, the three 890 micron continuum sources are expected to be point-like one at 430 micron as well.


SELF-CALIBRATION IS ACCEPTABLE IF NECESSARY: On the basis of our SMA observations (beam size = 0.85 arcsec x 0.78 arcsec at 335 GHz), we expect to have a bright unresolved continuum source (SMA1), which can be used for self-calibration. This object should have an intensity of 1.44 Jy per ALMA beam (0.54 arcsec x 0.082 arcsec at 691 GHz). Here we assumed the “beta-index” of the dust mass emissivity (i.e., kappa_0) of 1.5 when we converted the 890 micron intensity (1.89 Jy per SMA beam) to 430 micron. Even if we loose information of the absolute position due to self-calibration, we can still obtain (i) the direction of outflow lobes for the Scientific Goal 1, and (ii) the fluxes of three sources for the Scientific Goal 2.


CORRELATOR SETUP and DATA RATE:  We propose to employ the dual polarization 937.5 MHz bandwidth mode for the 12CO(6-5) line. The remaining three “Basebands” will be configured with the 1875 MHz width mode mainly for the continuum. The Baseband 2 will receive SO2 line which is one of the characteristic lines in HMCs. According to the OT, this setup requires a data rate of 21.74 Mb/s, exceeding the policy value, but it is ~1/3 of the maximum allowed value.


REQUESTED SENSITIVITY: The proposed observations will give us S/N ratios of the orders of 10^3 and 10^2 for the line and continuum, respectively. With the same fashion for the SMA1 described above, we estimate that SMA2 and SMA3 should have 430 micron intensities of 220 mJy/beam and 190 mJy/beam, respectively, yielding S/N-ratios of ~310 and ~270.  These S/N ratios are more than sufficient to absorb the possible uncertainties in the dust mass opacity coefficient which has been long-debated. The *13CO* (3-2) emission was detected with the peak intensity of ~9.5 Jy per SMA 0.8 arcsec beam. Therefore the *12CO* J=6-5 transition should have a range between ~5 to 50 Jy/beam due to variety of unknown factors (e.g., excitation conditions, [13CO]/[12CO] abundance ratio, and source beam coupling factors). However, we stress that the proposed line sensitivity of 10-sigma ~3E-5 Msun/(km/s) must suffice to assess the physical properties of the detected 12CO emission.  Last, the total requested time of 1.76 hrs to complete this project is below the “2-hrs limit” for requesting “best quartile” weather (“Proposer’s Guide, p. 20).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
